Former Mercedes-Benz designer Bela  Barenyi, 87, inventor of the safety chassis, is be accorded a place in the  Detroit Automotive Hall of Fame, the German automobile manufacturer announced.
He will join such names as Gottlieb Daimler, Robert Bosch, Rudolf Diesel  and Henry Ford.
Vienna-born Barenyi, the long-standing head of passenger car prototype  development at Mercedes Benz, developed the first accident crumple-zones for a  mass production vehicle, the Mercedes 180, in 1953, the company said.
He also invented the collapsible steering column and padded steering  wheel, it said.
